question: Hhheelllllloooo could you please do a something where the teen!fem!reader, Scarlett, Brie, and Elisabeth are always standing up for each other in interviews or something (like when people body shame, are being sexist, and etc) little angst and fluff please! BY THE WAY I LOVE YOU WRITING SO MUCH AND YOU ARE SO AMAZING ASHAHKDJ I LOVE READING WHAT YOU WRITE!! YOUR MY FAVORITE AUTHOR!!
answer:
I Don’t Owe You a Goddamn Thing (Avengers Cast x Teen!Fem!Reader)

A/N: Awwwww!!! I LOVE YOU!!! Hope you enjoy this fic! Sorry it’s so short! 

Cast members: Scarlett Johansson, Elizabeth Olsen, Brie Larson

Song Title: Nightmare by Halsey

Actor Fics Masterlist

Want to be in a Character Taglist? 

Warnings: sexist comments

Word Count: 559

*I do not own any of these gifs, credit to the owners.

“It’s so great to have you guys here,” The interviewer said as the camera started rolling, “I know you guys are all tired from doing interview all day.” We all agreed to that, chuckling a bit. You were so happy when you were told that you’d be doing interviews with Scarlett, Brie, and Elizabeth today. You were getting quite annoyed by Sebastian and Anthony’s teasing yesterday, you swore they were five-year-olds in older men’s bodies. You’re just a teenager and you felt more mature than them at times.

Everything seemed to be going fine, that was until one question came up, “(Y/N), it’s obvious that you are the youngest of the group, you’re only (Y/A) and I assume that you have to have someone else doing your stunts, not only because of your age but because you are a girl-”

“Jesus,” Elizabeth mumbled low enough that the interviewer didn’t hear.

“Were there ever times that you wished you could’ve done your own stunt?” The interviewer finished the question.

“I’m sorry, but you said you assumed?” Scarlett asked.

“Yes, well, you’re girls, you can’t do your stunts, I mean, you’re not strong like us men.”

You rolled your eyes and looked over at Brie, “isn’t there a video of you pushing a car or was I imagining things?”

She chuckled, “we must have been imagining the same thing if that were the case, us along with a million viewers.”

You smiled and looked over at the interviewer, “don’t assume things,” you began to say, “I did all my stunts because I knew I can handle it and frankly, I think women are tougher than men. After all, we push a baby out of a 10-centimeter hole and men can barely handle getting their eyebrows plucked.”

Scarlett stifled a laugh, “I-I’m sorry, I didn’t mean to offend you,” the interviewer said, his voice was a bit shaky.

You shook your head, “you see that’s the thing, you didn’t offend us, you pissed us off,” Elizabeth informed, “you came in here assuming things that weren’t true and spoke with confidence about how women were-”

“Elizabeth,” Scarlett warned in a motherly tone.

Elizabeth sighed, “right, I should calm down.”

“I think we’re done with this interview,” Brie said flashing the man a smile, “I have an appointment to get my eyebrows plucked,” Brie gave you a wink.

You all walked out of the room, “I think that went well,” you said.

Elizabeth laughed, linking arms with you, “men. When will they ever learn?”

Scarlett placed an arm around you, “I’m proud of you, for sticking up for yourself, for doing your own stunts, for just being you.”

“For being a woman that young girls can look up to,” Brie added, “the look on little girls faces when they see a girl superhero and when they see how tough they are.”

“It’s all worth it,” Elizabeth commented with a smile, “all this crap we get, it’s worth it when we see their faces.” They were right. In the end, you will always be tired of standing up for yourself, wishing that men would stop with their stereotypes of women but just seeing a little girl, with hope in their eyes, looking up at you like you put the stars in the sky. It’s worth it. You were fighting this fight for them.
